WILL AND TESTAMENT OF JAMES HOPEWELL
Maryland, 1800

In the name of God, Amen.

I, James Hopewell of Saint Mary's County, Maryland, being of sound mind and memory, do make and publish this my last will and testament, hereby revoking all former wills by me made.

ITEM FIRST: I give and bequeath to my beloved wife Mary Hopewell the use and occupation of my plantation and all household goods during her natural life.

ITEM SECOND: I give and bequeath to my son John Hopewell the following enslaved persons:
- Peter, a man aged about thirty-five years
- Mary, his wife, aged about twenty-eight years
- Thomas, their son, aged about ten years
- Sarah, their daughter, aged about seven years

ITEM THIRD: I give and bequeath to my daughter Sarah Hopewell the following enslaved persons:
- Hannah, a woman aged about thirty years
- Betsy, her daughter, aged about twelve years
- Rachel, aged about twenty years

ITEM FOURTH: I give to my wife during her life the use of the following enslaved persons:
- Jacob, a man aged about forty years
- Dinah, his wife, aged about thirty-five years
- Their children: Samuel, Moses, and Rebecca

ITEM FIFTH: Upon the death of my wife, all my real estate including my plantation of 300 acres shall be divided equally among my children John Hopewell and Sarah Hopewell.

ITEM SIXTH: I appoint my friend William Thompson and my son John Hopewell to be executors of this my last will and testament.

IN WITNESS WHEREOF, I have hereunto set my hand and seal this fifteenth day of March in the year of our Lord one thousand eight hundred.

James Hopewell [his mark]

Signed, sealed, published and declared by the said James Hopewell as and for his last will and testament in the presence of us, who at his request, in his presence, and in the presence of each other, have subscribed our names as witnesses thereto.

Witnesses:
William Thompson
Robert Davies
Thomas Anderson

Probated: April 10, 1825
Saint Mary's County, Maryland

